The course presents the concepts of nationalism and national movements in the eastern Baltic region and treats its influence on the development of society and culture from the late 18th century until World War I. The course will focus on the similarities and differences on Poland and Lithuania on one hand and Estonia and Latvia on the other. The former territories were Roman Catholic and had previous experience of independent statehood; the latter ones were provinces of foreign powers, sharing Lutheran cultural tradition. The whole region belonged to the Russian Empire.Objectives/eesmärkid:  The aim of the course is to develop the understanding of the problems of nationalism and national movements in the eastern Baltic littoralLearning outcomes/õpiväljund:  The student acquires systematic and comprehensive knowledge about the influence of nationalism on the development of society and culture from the late 18th century until World War I on the example of four countries of the eastern Baltic region (today's Estonia, Latvia, Lithuania and Poland). Knowledge about these developments will promote the understanding of the history of these countries and nationalities.
